</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DE65C504E8F4E4C4C8F2E13DD1B71FD6" pageId="216" pageNumber="217" type="distribution and habitat">
<paragraph id="DF99FC750EF7F3571A08981F42C67C85" pageId="216" pageNumber="217">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC5A6F43BE0D6BF550727799876718F0" pageId="216" pageNumber="217">
During the 19th and early 20th Centuries, 
<taxonomicName id="17B550DB814DF2C8E5E61918730C9A9D" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mecyclothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mecyclothorax haleakalae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="216" pageNumber="217" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haleakalae">Mecyclothorax haleakalae</taxonomicName>
was collected across the Waikamoi forest from Olinda to Ukulele Camp at elevations 1210-1675 m (Fig. 112). More recently it has been collected at Ukulele Pipeline (1525 m el.), and in yellow-pan traps along Kula Pipeline Rd (1183-1280 m el., UHIM) and Makawao-Maile Rd. (1293-1426 m el., UHIM). Aside from the yellow-pan traps, recent records have all been on 
<taxonomicName id="3C79D2F23DCBEC33B78F3EAB15634038" lsidName="koa" pageId="216" pageNumber="217" rank="species" species="koa">koa</taxonomicName>
, with beetles found under bark, or by application of pyrethrin fog to trunks of larger trees.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
